The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation
		 Thursday, February 26, 2004  Nation at a Glance				 																SC stay on Andhra cricket stadium				 																																																	New Delhi (PTI): The Supreme Court on Wednesday rejected a plea by the Hyderabad Cricket Association to lift the stay on construction activity at its new international cricket stadium, dampening its hopes of hosting an India-Australia tie in November at the proposed complex.				 																																																										A bench of Chief Justice V.. Khare and Justices S.B. Sinha and S.H. Kapadia dismissed an application moved by the association through secretary and national selector Shivlal Yadav seeking vacation of the stay granted on February 16.				 																																																										The stay was granted in favour of Indian Bank, which had moved the court alleging that the stadium could not be built at Uppal Mandal area in Hyderabad as the land was in its possession after being mortgaged by Penguin Textiles Ltd, which owed the bank money.				 																																																										Yadav, who was in intense consultation with lawyers after the interim order of the apex court, said he hoped that the dispute would be settled soon and construction resumed.				 																																																	sked whether he was hopeful of hosting a match between India and Australia in November at the new venue, he said: We are quite hopeful that the stadium will be completed by then to host the match. The cricket association has already spent over Rs 7 crore on the construction.				 																																																										Indian Bank had approached the Supreme Court against a compromise order passed by Andhra Pradesh High Court contending that though the land was mortgaged to it by the debtor, it was not made a party to the compromise deal.				 																Oxford fights Shivaji book caseMumbai (PTI): Bombay High Court has restrained Pune police from going ahead with investigations into a case registered against Oxford Printing Press and its representative in India for allegedly disrupting communal harmony by publishing distorted information in a book on Maratha king Chhatrapati Shivaji. 				 																																																										Admitting a petition filed by the printing press, the court also restrained the police from arresting its managing director in India, Manzar Khan, until the matter was disposed of.				 																																																										The petition, challenging the first information report filed by Pune police against the printing press, is likely to be heard after a month.The book Shivaji: Hindu King in Islamic India has been written by US-based James Laine. It had triggered strong protests  most notably the Sambhaji Brigade attack on the Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute in Pune  for erroneous information about the life of the Maratha king. 				 																																																										Appearing for Khan, criminal lawyer Mahesh Jethmalani argued that a scholarly book on history could not attract penal provisions for promoting enmity. He said the book did not intend to pitch one community against the other.				 																Daughter of a cop shot dead				 																																																	Indore (PTI): The daughter of a constable was shot dead by unidentified youths when she was coming out of a college after an exam here on Wednesday.				 																																																										Police said Pooja Kushwaha was shot in the head from a close range by two youths on a motorcycle as she walked out of the college after appearing in BCom first year examination. Pooja was rushed to hospital where she succumbed to the injury.				 																Boy murdered				 																																																	Indore (PTI): A boy lost his life over a game of cricket at Sanver on Tuesday night. Police said Jitendra Dhaneria had an altercation with two youths who were disrupting the game by driving a cycle near the pitch. Later in the night, the accused again picked up a quarrel and attacked Dhaneria, hacking him to death.				 																J amp;K probe				 																																																	Jammu (PTI): Jammu and Kashmir deputy chief minister Mangat Ram Sharma on Wednesday said the government has ordered an inquiry into the lathicharge on border migrants of Akhnoor who were on the way to Jammu on Tuesday to protest against the delay in implementation of a relief package for them. 				 																Infant in sewer				 																																																	Sirsa (PTI): A female newborn was found abandoned in a residential complex sewer at Mandi Kalanwali. Police said children playing cricket discovered the infant in a manhole while trying to retrieve a ball. They informed NGO Sahara whose volunteers rescued the infant.				 																Producer dead				 																																																	Chennai (PTI): Eminent film producer and Dadasaheb Phalke awardee Nagi Reddy died on Wednesday. Reddy was 92 and is survived by three sons and two daughters. His wife had passed away seven years ago. His family said the veteran film producer had been paralysed by a stroke six years ago and suffered another five months ago. 				 																Blindfolded driver				 																																																	Akola (PTI): A 14-year-old girl magician was arrested and fined Rs 1,000 for driving a car blindfolded. Police intercepted Suhani Shah when she reached Kotwali police station after driving blindfolded for nearly an hour. 																		Radio collars will be fixed on elephants in Buxa Tiger Reserve in Jalpaiguri to enable wildlife officials keep a watch on their movements and study their changing behaviour and food habits. It will also help control elephants from raiding the adjoining villages.
